Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Plea date on November 15, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

2:25 PM Defendant Sarah Ns Gunn appeared by video.  Attorney Gerard M Werner appeared by video for Sarah Ns Gunn.  Attorney Anthony A. Lambrecht appeared by video for State of Wisconsin.  Inducement made.  Defendant waives her right to a preliminary hearing.  Defendant is bound over for further proceedings.  Arraignment held. Defendant waives the reading of the Information. Not guilty plea entered to the charges contained in the Information. Defendant waives right to substitution.  States offer to be given to defense/defendant by June 24, 2022.
Scheduling conference scheduled for August 10, 2022 at 09:00 am.

1:47 pm - Prosecuting attorney Angelina R Scarpelli in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Sarah Ns Gunn appeared by video.  Attorney Gerard M Werner appeared by video for Sarah Ns Gunn. Defendant demands a preliminary hearing.
Adjourned plea hearing scheduled for May 18, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
Adjourned plea hearing on May 18, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

Defendant is remanded into custody on another matter. Court orders photos and prints at MTPD.
Bench warrant with service of officer thereon.
